{
  "texts": [
    "IntroductionThe main purpose of this paper is to provide a complete resolution of the so-called \"Lang's Flat Chain Conjecture\" [30, page 716].",
    "The conjecture concerns the structure of metric currents, which are objects of interest in Geometric Measure Theory.",
    "They are related to a number of geometric problems (in metric spaces) such as the Plateau problem [2], isoperimetric inequalities [7], flows of measures [37] and even geometric flows [1] (here currents are in particular used to define a suitable notion of distance [42]).",
    "Theory of metric currents was first developed by Ambrosio and Kirchheim in their seminal paper [2], where they also state what is popularly called the \"Flat Chain Conjecture\" [2, page 68].",
    "The conjecture states that metric k-currents of finite mass in R d with compact support are flat k-chains in the sense of Federer and Fleming (we provide relevant definitions as well as a detailed description of the problem later in Subsections 1.1 and 2.1)."
  ]
}